Kenya's Covid-19 fatalities have risen to 1,847 after another eight patients succumbed to the disease on Thursday. Some 61 patients have been admitted in the Intensive Care Unit due to Covid-19 complications, Health CS Mutahi Kagwe has said. From the number, 25 are on ventilator support, 27 on supplemental oxygen. In a statement to the media, Kagwe said 12 patients who are separately on supplementary oxygen are in general wards. The CS confirmed that 277 more people had tested positive for the virus from a sample size of 4,599 tests conducted in 24 hours. This represents a positivity rate of 6.0 per cent rising the country's positive to 105,057. The cumulative tests stand at 1,282,799. Kagwe said that there are 336 patients currently admitted in various hospitals across the country. Another, 1,397 patients are on the home-based care programme. Meanwhile, 119 patients have recovered from the disease out of which 79 were from the Homebased care program while 40 were discharged from various health facilities. Kenya's recoveries now stand at 86,497. From the new cases reported on Thursday, 221 are Kenyans while 56 are foreigners. In terms of gender, 173 are males while 104 are females and the youngest in a three-year-old child and the oldest is 89. Nairobi has 194 cases, Nakuru 18, Kiambu 17, Mombasa 11, Laikipia 8, Kajiado 7, Machakos 6, Uasin Gishu 5, Siaya 2, Makueni 2, Meru 1, Nandi 1, Narok 1, Nyandarua 1, Nyeri 1, Taita Taveta 1 and Kisumu 1.Quote Tweet